          <avActivityHighlights>As a consequence of the northeasterly wind the prevalence of the avalanche prone locations will increase as the day progresses.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>As a consequence of a freshening wind from northeasterly directions, further wind slabs will form in the course of the day. These can in some places be released, even by a single winter sport participant. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In particular on steep slopes the avalanches can be released in the various wind slab layers and reach large size in isolated cases. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Several mostly small natural dry avalanches are possible on very steep slopes. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; High altitudes and the high Alpine regions: Backcountry touring calls for careful route selection.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>In some regions 10 to 15 cm of snow fell yesterday above approximately 1600 m. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of new snow and a moderate to strong wind from northeasterly directions, further wind slabs will form. High altitudes and the high Alpine regions: Over a wide area various wind slab layers are lying on a hard crust. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In the vicinity of peaks snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; Individual weak layers exist in the old snowpack in particular on shady slopes.</snowpackStructureComment>
        </BulletinMeasurements>
      </bulletinResultsOf>
    </Bulletin>
